      "title": "Sharks' cancer secret also puts them at risk: study",
      "url": "https://www.monash.edu/news/articles/sharks-cancer-secret-also-puts-them-at-risk-study",
      "content": "New international Monash University-led research has explained the reasons for and implications of low cancer rates in sharks, which until now have remained a decades long mystery. In a world-first collaborative international study, co-led by Monash University's Australian Regenerative Medicine ..."
    },
    {
      "title": "Sharks can get cancer — NCI confirms — Lenz",
      "url": "https://lenz.io/c/sharks-do-not-get-cancer-claim-294d69f7",
      "content": "Sharks are not cancer-proof. Authoritative medical sources and peer-reviewed studies document both benign and malignant tumors in sharks and explicitly identify the claim as a myth. Research on low mutation rates or distinctive immune genes may suggest biological differences, but it does not show that sharks never develop cancer."
    },
    {
      "title": "Sharks' slow evolution explains low cancer rates - Geographical",
      "url": "https://geographical.co.uk/news/sharks-slow-evolution-explains-low-cancer-rates",
      "content": "Study unveils secret of low cancer rates in sharks, but slow shark evolution means difficulties adapting to changes in the ocean environment."
    },
    {
      "title": "Low cancer rate in sharks comes with an evolutionary cost",
      "url": "https://divemagazine.com/scuba-diving-news/low-cancer-rate-in-sharks-comes-with-an-evolutionary-cost",
      "content": "Sharks suffer from a very low incidence of cancer but a new study, led by Monash University's Australian Regenerative Medicine Institute (ARMI), has found that the reasons behind this may also mean they are unable to adapt to rapid environmental change. Sharks play a vital role in the ecological health of the oceans; larger sharks are often classed as apex predators in their environments ..."
